{{orphan|date=June 2011}}

'''Diag Human''' is a [[Liechtenstein]]-incorporated [[blood plasma]] trading company, established by [[Swiss]]-[[Czechs|Czech]] entrepreneur Josef Šťáva (born 17 March 1950 in [[Prague]]) in the 1980s.<ref name="folkman">{{cite web|last1=Folkman|first1=Ted|title=Case of the day: Diag Human vs. Czech Ministry of Health|url=https://lettersblogatory.com/2014/08/19/case-day-diag-human-v-czech-ministry-health/|website=Letters Blogatory|date=19 August 2014|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref> The stated aim of the company was to help "currency-deficient Eastern Bloc states acquire modern blood plasma technology".<ref name="folkman"/>

== Lawsuit against the Czech government ==

The company received media attention in the 1996, when it filed a lawsuit against the [[Czech government]] in Prague Commercial Court, for defamation and unfair competition. The company claimed that the Health Minister had contacted [[Novo Nordisk]], a major business partner of Diag Human, to dissuade the company from doing business with them, which led to the failure of Diag Human's business in the country.<ref name="folkman"/> The two parties agreed to enter arbitration,<ref name="folkman"/> and the case became one of the largest cases of commercial litigation in the history of Czech Republic.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120321091048/http://www.praguetravelguide.info/article-280686-en.html An article from PragueTravelGuide.info.]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2007/04/30/2565288.htm |title=Prague dissatisfied with firm assisting in Diag Human case-server |work=Czech News Agency |date=30 April 2007 |accessdate=26 November 2013}}</ref> In 2008, the court found in favour of Diag Human, awarding around $650 million to the company.<ref name="folkman"/>

