'''Urea perchlorate''' is a sheet-shaped crystallite with good chemical stability and strong hygroscopicity. It has usage as an [[oxidizer]] in [[liquid explosives]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Liu|first1=Jiping|title=Liquid Explosives|date=2015|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783662458464|page=6}}</ref> including [[Underwater explosion|underwater blasting]].<ref>{{cite patent|number = US3952655 A| title = Underwater blasting method and explosives and devices used therein| pubdate = 27 Apr 1976 | fdate = 26 Feb 1974| pridate = 27 Feb 1973| inventor = Masao Kusakabe, Shuzo Fuziwara, Kazuo Shiino }}</ref>
== Synthesis ==
The compound is synthesized by gradual addition of urea into a perchloric acid solution:
:CO(NH<sub>2</sub>)<sub>2</sub> + HClO<sub>4</sub> → CO(NH<sub>2</sub>)<sub>2</sub>·HClO<sub>4</sub>
An alternative route is addition of urea to hydrochloric acid solution, followed by addition of sodium perchlorate, and filtration of the salt.
:NaClO<sub>4</sub>·H<sub>2</sub>O + CO(NH<sub>2</sub>)<sub>2</sub> + HCl → CO(NH<sub>2</sub>)<sub>2</sub>·HClO<sub>4</sub> + NaCl + H<sub>2</sub>O
